    The "golden rules" I want you to live by
    These are the rules I follow when designing React applications:

        - Pages compose; they don't contain business logic. A page should mainly arrange components and orchestrate the screen.
        - Components render UI. They should be focused on presentation and user interaction, not networking.
        - Hooks coordinate React behavior. They manage state, effects, and connect the UI to your business logic.
        - Services contain business rules. If you're transforming data, enforcing business behavior, or deciding what should happen, it belongs here.
        - API files only communicate with the server. No data transformation, no UI decisionsвЂ”just requests and responses.
        - Stores manage client-side state. They don't fetch data directly or implement business rules.
        - Utilities are pure functions. Given the same input, they always produce the same output and don't modify external state.
        - Types define your contracts. They describe the shape of data and keep your codebase type-safe.
        - Validation schemas define what is acceptable input. Keep validation separate from rendering logic.
        - Constants eliminate "magic numbers" and repeated strings. If a value is reused or has meaning, give it a name.

